[00:00.39]	[The same. A hall in Timon's house.,]
[00:01.17]	[Enter FLAVIUS, with many bills in his hand]
[00:01.95]FLAVIUS	No care, no stop! so senseless of expense,
[00:04.95]	That he will neither know how to maintain it,
[00:08.28]	Nor cease his flow of riot: takes no account
[00:11.54]	How things go from him, nor resumes no care
[00:14.73]	Of what is to continue: never mind
[00:17.34]	Was to be so unwise, to be so kind.
[00:19.95]	What shall be done? he will not hear, till feel:
[00:23.34]	I must be round with him, now he comes from hunting.
[00:27.06]	Fie, fie, fie, fie!
[00:28.49]	[Enter CAPHIS, and the Servants of Isidore and Varro]
[00:29.28]CAPHIS	Good even, Varro: what,
[00:31.04]	You come for money?
[00:32.67]Varro's Servant	Is't not your business too?
[00:34.82]CAPHIS	It is: and yours too, Isidore?
[00:37.04]Isidore's Servant	It is so.
[00:38.01]CAPHIS	Would we were all discharged!
[00:40.30]Varro's Servant	I fear it.
[00:41.34]CAPHIS	Here comes the lord.
[00:43.04]	[Enter TIMON, ALCIBIADES, and Lords, &c]
[00:43.82]TIMON	So soon as dinner's done, we'll forth again,
[00:47.01]	My Alcibiades. With me? what is your will?
[00:50.01]CAPHIS	My lord, here is a note of certain dues.
[00:52.95]TIMON	Dues! Whence are you?
[00:54.64]CAPHIS	Of Athens here, my lord.
[00:56.53]TIMON	Go to my steward.
[00:58.03]CAPHIS	Please it your lordship, he hath put me off
[01:01.23]	To the succession of new days this month:
[01:04.30]	My master is awaked by great occasion
[01:07.16]	To call upon his own, and humbly prays you
[01:10.29]	That with your other noble parts you'll suit
[01:13.62]	In giving him his right.
[01:15.58]TIMON	Mine honest friend,
[01:17.21]	I prithee, but repair to me next morning.
[01:20.21]CAPHIS	Nay, good my lord,--
[01:21.71]TIMON	Contain thyself, good friend.
[01:23.92]Varro's Servant	One Varro's servant, my good lord,--
[01:26.47]Isidore's Servant	From Isidore;
[01:27.71]	He humbly prays your speedy payment.
[01:30.45]CAPHIS	If you did know, my lord, my master's wants--
[01:33.58]Varro's Servant	'Twas due on forfeiture, my lord, six weeks And past.
[01:37.23]Isidore's Servant	Your steward puts me off, my lord;
[01:39.77]	And I am sent expressly to your lordship.
[01:42.84]TIMON	Give me breath.
[01:44.21]	I do beseech you, good my lords, keep on;
[01:47.14]	I'll wait upon you instantly.
[01:49.42]	[Exeunt ALCIBIADES and Lords]
[01:50.21]	[To FLAVIUS]
[01:50.99]	Come hither: pray you,
[01:52.75]	How goes the world, that I am thus encounter'd
[01:56.14]	With clamourous demands of date-broke bonds,
[01:59.40]	And the detention of long-since-due debts,
[02:02.53]	Against my honour?
[02:04.10]FLAVIUS	Please you, gentlemen,
[02:05.86]	The time is unagreeable to this business:
[02:08.92]	Your importunacy cease till after dinner,
[02:11.99]	That I may make his lordship understand
[02:14.99]	Wherefore you are not paid.
[02:17.14]TIMON	Do so, my friends. See them well entertain'd.
[02:20.33]	[Exit]
[02:21.12]FLAVIUS	Pray, draw near.
[02:22.49]	[Exit]
[02:23.27]	[Enter APEMANTUS and Fool]
[02:24.05]CAPHIS	Stay, stay, here comes the fool with Apemantus:
[02:27.38]	let's ha' some sport with 'em.
[02:29.59]Varro's Servant	Hang him, he'll abuse us.
[02:31.55]Isidore's Servant	A plague upon him, dog!
[02:33.38]Varro's Servant	How dost, fool?
[02:34.68]APEMANTUS	Dost dialogue with thy shadow?
[02:37.03]Varro's Servant	I speak not to thee.
[02:38.72]APEMANTUS	No,'tis to thyself.
[02:40.29]	[To the Fool]
[02:41.07]	Come away.
