[02:45.38]APEMANTUS	No, thou stand'st single, thou'rt not on him yet.
[02:48.83]CAPHIS	Where's the fool now?
[02:50.59]APEMANTUS	He last asked the question. Poor rogues, and
[02:53.79]	usurers' men! bawds between gold and want!
[02:56.79]All Servants	What are we, Apemantus?
[02:58.61]APEMANTUS	Asses.
[02:59.40]All Servants	Why?
[03:00.05]APEMANTUS	That you ask me what you are, and do not know
[03:03.37]	yourselves. Speak to 'em, fool.
[03:05.59]Fool	How do you, gentlemen?
[03:07.35]All Servants	Gramercies, good fool: how does your mistress?
[03:10.61]Fool	She's e'en setting on water to scald such chickens
[03:14.33]	as you are. Would we could see you at Corinth!
[03:17.66]APEMANTUS	Good! gramercy.
[03:18.96]	[Enter Page]
[03:19.74]Fool	Look you, here comes my mistress' page.
[03:22.55]Page	[To the Fool] Why, how now, captain! what do you
[03:25.42]	in this wise company? How dost thou, Apemantus?
[03:28.74]APEMANTUS	Would I had a rod in my mouth, that I might answer
[03:32.39]	thee profitably.
[03:33.83]Page	Prithee, Apemantus, read me the superscription of
[03:37.35]	these letters: I know not which is which.
[03:40.35]APEMANTUS	Canst not read?
[03:41.72]Page	No.
[03:42.31]APEMANTUS	There will little learning die then, that day thou
[03:45.96]	art hanged. This is to Lord Timon; this to
[03:49.02]	Alcibiades. Go; thou wast born a bastard, and thou't
[03:52.68]	die a bawd.
[03:53.78]Page	Thou wast whelped a dog, and thou shalt famish a
[03:57.31]	dog's death. Answer not; I am gone.
[03:59.85]	[Exit]
[04:00.63]APEMANTUS	E'en so thou outrunnest grace. Fool, I will go with
[04:04.28]	you to Lord Timon's.
[04:05.98]Fool	Will you leave me there?
[04:07.94]APEMANTUS	If Timon stay at home. You three serve three usurers?
[04:11.72]All Servants	Ay; would they served us!
[04:13.67]APEMANTUS	So would I,--as good a trick as ever hangman served thief.
[04:17.72]Fool	Are you three usurers' men?
[04:19.80]All Servants	Ay, fool.
[04:20.72]Fool	I think no usurer but has a fool to his servant: my
[04:24.44]	mistress is one, and I am her fool. When men come
[04:27.96]	to borrow of your masters, they approach sadly, and
[04:31.61]	go away merry; but they enter my mistress' house
[04:35.06]	merrily, and go away sadly: the reason of this?
